  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a common disease that develops from degeneration of the
      aortic wall. The natural history of AAA is gradual expansion and if left untreated may result
      in rupture and death. The mechanism of the development of this disease is unknown however it
      appears to be multifactorial and possibly related to degradation processes within the
      arterial wall. There is growing evidence that Angiotensin receptor blockers ( ARBS) may have
      an inhibitory effect on remodelling processes within the arterial wall, thus inhibiting
      degeneration of the vessel wall.

      Study hypothesis: ARBS are associated with smaller diameters of aortas among hypertensive
      patients, and are associated with a lower rate of aortic expansion compared to other
      antihypertensive drugs.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
